<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Hey Everyone :3<br>
<br>
Ok... the following is a tutorial on how to make Screentones using Photoshop O_O. It's very simple and I'm sure a few people out there doing it already... but as far as I know, the general fanartist public doesn't know how. (i know i didn't) This particular tutorial is good for making tones for WEB COMICS only... if you would like to use this technique forprint you would prolly add a few hundred to most of the #s involved for a high res version.<br>
<br>
Ok. Here we go, First open one of your comic pages, BW line art in Photoshop and make sure its in grayscale mode.<br>
<br>
2 - create a new layer, and then use the rectangular selection tool to select the whole page area on the new layer.<br>
<br>
3 - select a shade of grey from your color picker, and use the fll bucket to fill the entire selected area. now go to edit/cut and cut the grey fill.<br>
<br>
4 - open a new file, (it should be the exact dimensions of your last selection automatically) and paste the grey fill into the new file. we are doing this so that the line art will not be converted to screens too and you will have crisp lines :3 call yer new file - screen<br>
<br>
5 - the fun part - Go to Image/mode/bitmap it will ask you flatten layers? click OK. next up is the input/output #s. your input should be 72 pixels per inch if yer doing this for web, tho the default setting is 300 i think, don't matter either way. set your output at something wayhigher... i use 1500 tho my computer can barely handle it :3<br>
<br>
The idea here is... if you have your setting lower the dots break down into squares, diamonds, and houndstooth like patterns... we just want dots so at higher res... you can make nice dots :3<br>
<br>
check off halftone screen for method then click OK<br>
<br>
6 - frequency. this means the amount of dots that are gonna make the screen. frequency should be set around 30 to 50 or so. You can totally play with the settings...im just doing this for example. Angle should be 45 for straight on tone that's aligned perfect. Shape - round. Now click OK.<br>
<br>
7 - go to View/Actual pixels to get a good look at your tones now :3<br>
<br>
8 - resize your image. i resized this one to 1445 by 893 wide. it makes a nice large dot pattern  you can play with the frequency and resizing to git different patterns :3<br>
<br>
9 - convert back to greayscale and drag it back to your comic page or illo. set it's layer mode to multiply and use eraser, airbrush, selection tools to scrape out whites like real screentone  you can save this sheet and make a library of your favorite tones :3<br>
<br>
none of the techniques and #s here are the best way to do it... experiment. learn faster and better ways and shortcuts. share them with others, if we all get better as artists, make more quality work, our industry gets respect, we get more control in our projects and eventually make more money or somethin O_O help each other out. learn from each other. inspire each other. express yourself. isnt that what art is all about?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <p><img src="http://www.spikescafe.com/shellt.gif"> <a href="http://www.spikescafe.com/index.html">Leonardo de Spikey</a> (Battles the Foot Clan thanks to wantsomepie)<BR><table width=464 height=64 border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
